    <string name="ph_info">The ph inside your bucket can affect the way your plant takes in nutrients and water.
        Each plant is different but typically has a range between 4-9. Take time to look up what is a good
        range for your plants and aim to keep the water within that range by adding either PH+ or PH-.</string>
    <string name="ppm_info">PPM/TDS is a measure of the parts per million/total dissolved solids within your bucket.
        Ideally you should keep a note of what the water in your home naturally has so you can adjust your nutrients as needed.
        Take a look online for a mixture of nutrient solutions and suggested amounts per litre/gallon of water and add it to your water.
        Compare against your tap water levels so you have a baseline and a full nutrient solution level.
        As your plant absorbs water it will absorb nutrients as well, the ph and ppm will change and as needed you may need to top up as time goes on.</string>
    <string name="water_level_info">Keep an eye on your water level as your plant may drink water faster than you expect!</string>
    <string name="humidity_info">Humidity is the amount of moisture in your air. This can affect how plants will absorb light and nutrients from the water.
